Use **`dotnet-trace`** to collect `HttpClient` event source diagnostics:

```bash
# Install the tool (if not already)
dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace

# Collect HttpClient + networking events
dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> \
  --providers "System.Net.Http,Microsoft-Extensions-Logging"
```

For **richer HTTP request/response detail** (including status codes and timing), enable `HttpHandlerDiagnosticListener` via `ActivitySource`:

```bash
dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> \
  --providers "System.Net.Http,Microsoft-Extensions-Logging,Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpLogging"
```

**Better approach — add structured logging in code** for actionable data:

```csharp
// In Program.cs or Startup
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("DownstreamApi")
    .AddHttpMessageHandler<LoggingDelegatingHandler>();

// Custom handler
public class LoggingDelegatingHandler(ILogger<LoggingDelegatingHandler> logger)
    : DelegatingHandler
{
    protected override async Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        var sw = Stopwatch.StartNew();
        var response = await base.SendAsync(request, ct);
        sw.Stop();

        if (!response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            logger.LogWarning(
                "HTTP {Method} {Uri} returned {StatusCode} in {ElapsedMs}ms",
                request.Method, request.RequestUri,
                (int)response.StatusCode, sw.ElapsedMilliseconds);
        }

        return response;
    }
}
```

**Summary:**

| Approach | When to use |
|---|---|
| `dotnet-trace` | Live prod debugging, no code change |
| `DelegatingHandler` logging | Permanent observability with status codes + latency |
| OpenTelemetry (`System.Net.Http` instrumentation) | If you already use OTel for distributed tracing |

For your specific case (finding **which** requests get 500s and **how long** they take), the `DelegatingHandler` approach gives you the most direct signal.
